english:
  title: A Prayer for the Imperial Blessing
  author: Seok Bok-am
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Buddha's compassion runs deep in benefiting all things,
    Responding to the manifold needs of sentient beings.
    It is the duty of monks to pray for the nation's longevity—
    How much more so when receiving such exceptional grace.

    Thus we rely upon the dharma's way to beseech the Emperor's years.
    This temple of the Ciyu lineage is where Master Chongjing once dwelt,
    A sacred ground where scholars of the Nine Mountains gather,
    Where only a great Chan master of the age can preside.

    As for one such as I—with shallow roots and dull nature,
    With dim understanding and scattered learning—
    I am ashamed even to stand among my fellow monks,
    How could I dare hope to enter the master's inner chamber?

    Yet fortune has granted me this auspicious age,
    Steeped in abundant imperial grace.
    This unworthy small frame has received what is hard to bear—
    A great vessel beyond my measure.

    At first, startled as one waking from a dream of Nanke,
    I seemed to doubt my senses.
    But now, dwelling in peace, I feel as one ascending to the celestial realms.

    To repay even a fraction of this vast blessing,
    I must redouble my efforts in spiritual practice.
    Thus I kindle this altar of incense,
    And raise my prayers higher than the mountain peaks.

    The monastery restored, the ancient ways endure.
    The bells and drums renewed, they shine with new radiance.
    Where sincere devotion reaches, Buddha's response pervades all.

    I humbly pray: May the Buddha's aid swiftly bless the Emperor,
    May heavenly blessings descend in abundance.
    May he dwell in longevity with the Empress in the inner palace,
    Untouched by the turning of the seasons,
    Ever receiving the Emperor's tender care,
    That the realm may rest in peace eternal.
  footnotes:
    - 'Nanke (南柯): A reference to the classical tale ''The Governor of Nanke,'' a famous dream allegory symbolizing the illusory nature of worldly fortune.'
    - 'Nine Mountains (九山): Refers to the nine major centers of Seon Buddhism in Korea.'
    - 'Inner chamber (入室): A Zen Buddhist term for transmission of the dharma from master to disciple.'
